==English==

===Etymology===
From {{L.}} ''[[ubique]]'', everywhere

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/juːˈbɪkwɪtəs/}}, {{SAMPA|/ju:"bIkwIt@s/}}
*{{audio|en-uk-ubiquitous.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
*{{audio|en-us-ubiquitous.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj-notcomp}}

very important 
unavoidable


====Quotations====
*'''1851''' — [[w:Herman Melville|Herman Melville]], ''[[s:Moby Dick|Moby Dick]]'', Ch. 41
*:One of the wild suggestions referred to, as at last coming to be linked with the White Whale in the minds of the superstitiously inclined, was the unearthly conceit that Moby Dick was '''ubiquitous'''; that he had actually been encountered in opposite latitudes at one and the same instant of time.
*'''1927-1929''' — [[w:Mahatma Gandhi|Mahatma Gandhi]], ''[[s:An Autobiography or The Story of my Experiments with Truth|An Autobiography or The Story of my Experiments with Truth]], Part V (XII) [[s:The Stain of Indigo|The Stain of Indigo]]''
*:I returned to the Ashram. The '''ubiquitous''' Rajkumar was there too.

====Synonyms====
*(''being everywhere''): [[omnipresent]]
*(''seeming to appear everywhere at the same time''): [[ever-present]]

